  "prompt": "Can the sun melt snow in below freezing temperatures?",
  "response": "Yes, the sun can definitely melt snow even when the air temperature is below freezing (0\u00b0C or 32\u00b0F). Here's why:\n\n*   **Solar Radiation:** The sun emits energy in the form of electromagnetic radiation. When this radiation strikes the snow, some of it is absorbed. This absorbed energy is converted into heat.\n\n*   **Melting Point:** If the snow absorbs enough solar energy, its surface temperature can rise to its melting point (0\u00b0C or 32\u00b0F). Once the surface reaches the melting point, further absorbed energy will cause the snow to melt rather than increase its temperature.\n\n*   **Factors Influencing Melting:**\n    *   **Sun Angle:** The angle at which the sun's rays hit the snow surface is crucial. A more direct (perpendicular) angle results in more energy absorption.\n    *   **Cloud Cover:** Clouds can block or reduce the amount of solar radiation reaching the snow.\n    *   **Snow Albedo:** Albedo is the reflectivity of a surface. Fresh, bright white snow has a high albedo, meaning it reflects a large portion of the incoming solar radiation. Older, dirtier snow has a lower albedo and absorbs more energy.\n    *   **Wind:** Wind can affect the rate of melting through two mechanisms: increased evaporation which can cool the snow pack or it can bring in warmer air.\n    *   **Humidity:** Low humidity increases evaporation, which cools the snow and slows melting.\n\n*   **Sublimation:** In very dry, cold conditions, snow can also sublimate (go directly from solid to gas) even below freezing. This process also requires energy from the sun or the environment.\n\n**In Summary:**\n\nEven though the air temperature is below freezing, the sun's energy can warm the surface of the snow above freezing, causing it to melt. The rate of melting depends on several factors, including sun angle, cloud cover, snow albedo, and wind conditions.\n",
